Task 5: Firewall & Network Protection
A firewall controls traffic flowing in and out of your device via ports. Think of it as a security guard checking the ID of everything trying to enter or exit your network.
Windows Firewall offers three profiles:
Domain: Used when the computer is connected to a corporate domain controller.
Private: Used for trusted home or work networks.
Public: The default for untrusted networks (like coffee shop Wi-Fi). This is the most restrictive profile.
You can manage these via the GUI or using the command WF.msc.

Answer the questions below
Question: If you were connected to airport Wi-Fi, what most likely will be the active firewall profile?
Based on the definitions above, an airport offers a public connection. You can also verify this by checking the active profile in the Firewall settings.
Answer: Public network



